WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.320
to speak about histiocytic neoplasms, my financial disclosures.

00:00:07.620 --> 00:00:14.160
So histiocytic neoplasms, including Langerhans, Erdheim-Chester, Rosler-Dorfman,

00:00:14.340 --> 00:00:20.120
are a rare group of diseases where having 15 patients makes me somehow a quote-unquote expert.

00:00:22.200 --> 00:00:28.260
It's a heterogeneous group of disease characterized by infiltration of organs by these clonal myeloid cells

00:00:28.260 --> 00:00:34.440
where the MAP kinase pathway mutation arises in a precursor cell.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:40.740
And depending on which stage of this differentiation, the precursor cells are affected,

00:00:41.100 --> 00:00:45.780
you can get multisystem disease or low-risk disease or a single-system disease.

00:00:46.580 --> 00:00:51.980
And as you can see in the figure here, this is a representative of a patient with Langerhans

00:00:51.980 --> 00:00:57.640
where there's skin involvement, lung involvement, bone involvement, and also CNS involvement.

00:00:58.260 --> 00:01:05.300
And the NCCN guideline has a really nice table of the characteristic features of histiocytic neoplasms.

00:01:05.300 --> 00:01:12.960
Some of the buzzwords you might hear are, for Erdheim-Chester, you might hear osteosclerosis of the bone

00:01:12.960 --> 00:01:17.240
or hairy kidney or periaortic infiltration.

00:01:17.940 --> 00:01:24.840
And for Langerhans, you might see lung involvement and bone involvement, characteristically.

00:01:25.300 --> 00:01:27.800
And for Rosler-Dorfman, you might see some lymphadenopathy.

00:01:28.260 --> 00:01:37.320
We've learned recently that the MAP kinase pathway mutation really plays a critical role

00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:42.900
in the pathogenesis of these Langerhans and Erdheim-Chester where about half of the patients

00:01:42.900 --> 00:01:53.300
have the BRAV BRAF mutation and another about 30% of the people have the MAP to kinase pathway mutation.

00:01:54.140 --> 00:01:58.240
Rosler-Dorfman disease is a little bit different from the MAP kinase pathway mutation.

00:01:58.260 --> 00:02:07.520
The other two, they don't have a lot of the BRAV mutation, but has the MAP to K1 mutations in about 45% of the case

00:02:07.520 --> 00:02:10.320
and the NRAS mutation in 45% of the cases.

00:02:13.280 --> 00:02:19.780
So then naturally, if you have a BRAV mutation, you want to start targeting it to see if that will be effective.

00:02:20.780 --> 00:02:27.260
Prior to these targeted therapies, people were treated with cytotoxic chemotherapy, including cladribine.

00:02:28.260 --> 00:02:39.480
And this study in 2017 was called a VE basket study, included patients with various non-melanoma cancers

00:02:39.480 --> 00:02:42.700
who have BRAV BRAF mutations.

00:02:43.840 --> 00:02:52.080
And 26 patients of these had histiocytic neoplasms and were treated with bimerafenib, 960 mg twice daily,

00:02:53.020 --> 00:02:57.160
and with a remarkable overall response rate of 61.5%.

00:02:57.160 --> 00:02:57.160
And this study was done in 2017.

00:02:57.160 --> 00:02:57.180
And this study was done in 2017.

00:02:57.180 --> 00:02:57.180
And this study was done in 2017.

00:02:57.180 --> 00:02:57.200
And this study was done in 2017.

00:02:57.200 --> 00:02:57.240
And this study was done in 2017.

00:02:57.240 --> 00:02:57.280
And this study was done in 2017.

00:02:57.280 --> 00:02:57.320
And this study was done in 2017.

00:02:57.320 --> 00:02:57.340
And this study was done in 2017.

00:02:57.340 --> 00:02:57.400
And this study was done in 2017.

00:02:57.400 --> 00:02:57.420
And this study was done in 2017.

00:02:57.420 --> 00:02:57.480
And this study was done in 2017.

00:02:57.480 --> 00:02:57.580
And this study was done in 2017.

00:02:57.580 --> 00:02:57.620
And this study was done in 2017.

00:02:57.620 --> 00:03:01.880
and a two-year progression-free survival of 86%.

00:03:01.880 --> 00:03:13.500
So this study led to the approval of imirafinib in VRAF BRAF mutated histiocytic neoplasms.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:20.340
Now, but half of the patients do not harbor the VRAF mutation, so then you're wondering

00:03:20.340 --> 00:03:22.840
if you can get the MEK inhibitor to work.

00:03:22.840 --> 00:03:29.960
So this study included 18 patients with ECD, LCH, and RDD, and these patients were treated

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:36.380
with covimetinib, 16 milligrams, and another remarkable overall response rate.

00:03:36.680 --> 00:03:42.360
And by the way, these patients had various types of mutations, as you can see in the

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:50.000
figures below, but the overall response rate was about 89% by PET response criteria.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:51.620
All responses were durable.

00:03:52.440 --> 00:03:56.340
And there were no prior resistance later on.

00:03:56.620 --> 00:04:04.280
So this study led to the FDA approval of covimetinib in histiocytic neoplasm patients, regardless

00:04:04.280 --> 00:04:05.600
of their mutation status.

00:04:09.480 --> 00:04:15.440
And then we haven't had anything really groundbreaking for a long time.

00:04:15.540 --> 00:04:20.580
There were various VRAF inhibitors and MEK inhibitors that we, you know, we saw that

00:04:20.580 --> 00:04:21.060
they work.

00:04:21.300 --> 00:04:22.040
That's a no-brainer.

00:04:22.040 --> 00:04:28.700
But then recently, there was a study in RDD, where patients were treated with lenalidomide,

00:04:28.760 --> 00:04:35.120
and the thought is that the anti-inflammatory properties of lenalidomide might help in patients

00:04:35.120 --> 00:04:35.640
with RDD.

00:04:36.820 --> 00:04:42.820
So 23 patients were treated with lenalidomide and dexamethasone, and at a medium follow-up

00:04:42.820 --> 00:04:48.520
of 26 months, the two-year overall survival was 100%, and 17 of the 23 patients had response.

00:04:50.020 --> 00:04:51.640
So this is also on the NCCN guidelines.

00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:57.180
And patients who have failed other therapies as an option.

00:04:59.960 --> 00:05:06.260
So there are still several areas of unmet need, and it's just like neoplasms.

00:05:06.740 --> 00:05:11.140
And one thing is, are we ever going to achieve cure?

00:05:11.300 --> 00:05:16.320
Because we've observed that patients who are on targeted therapy, who go off on these

00:05:16.320 --> 00:05:21.180
therapies, inevitably relapse in 50% to 80% of the cases.

00:05:21.640 --> 00:05:26.020
Although they do respond to re-treatment.

00:05:28.200 --> 00:05:34.520
And another sort of devastating side effect or clinical presentation of these histoacetic

00:05:34.520 --> 00:05:36.840
neoplasms is neurodegeneration.

00:05:37.560 --> 00:05:40.840
And this occurs mostly in patients with LCH and ECD.

00:05:41.740 --> 00:05:47.920
And clinical manifestations include cerebellar ataxia, dysarthria, cognitive impairment,

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:49.760
and behavior abnormalities.

00:05:50.040 --> 00:05:51.240
It's thought to be.

00:05:51.240 --> 00:05:58.560
So there's a lot to be said about neurodegeneration from these BRAF-mutated cells that are predominantly

00:05:58.560 --> 00:06:03.960
in the microglia and the cerebellar area that leads to these neurodegeneration.

00:06:03.960 --> 00:06:08.420
And unfortunately, these targeted therapies and cytotoxic chemotherapy might slow down

00:06:08.420 --> 00:06:09.420
the progression.

00:06:09.420 --> 00:06:11.880
However, it is thought to be irreversible.

00:06:11.880 --> 00:06:16.460
So these are my summary slides and references.

00:06:16.460 --> 00:06:18.460
And thank you.
